name=\"description\" content=\"Abstract page for arXiv paper 2607.04814v1: Evaluating the Effect of Linguistic Relatedness on Cross-Lingual Transfer in Large Multilingual Automatic Speech Recognition\"><meta property=\"og:type\" content=\"website\" />\n22\t<meta property=\"og:site_name\" content=\"arXiv.org\" />\n23\t<meta property=\"og:title\" content=\"Evaluating the Effect of Linguistic Relatedness on Cross-Lingual Transfer in Large Multilingual Automatic Speech Recognition\" />\n24\t<meta property=\"og:url\" content=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.04814v1\" />\n25\t<meta property=\"og:image\" content=\"/static/browse/0.3.4/images/arxiv-logo-fb.png\" />\n26\t<meta property=\"og:image:secure_url\" content=\"/static/browse/0.3.4/images/arxiv-logo-fb.png\" />\n27\t<meta property=\"og:image:width\" content=\"1200\" />\n28\t<meta property=\"og:image:height\" content=\"700\" />\n29\t<meta property=\"og:image:alt\" content=\"arXiv logo\"/>\n30\t<meta property=\"og:description\" content=\"Extending automatic speech recognition (ASR) to low-resource African languages is constrained by the prohibitive demands of data collection at scale. A promising direction is to leverage linguistic relatedness to enhance cross-lingual transfer from a related auxiliary language to the low-resource target by sequentially adapting on both. Although this strategy has shown meaningful improvements in small ASR models, its effectiveness in large ASR remains unclear. We extend this framework to large multilingual ASR through a systematic controlled experimental design spanning six factors, two Africa-centric corpora, and four large ASR models, isolating whether linguistic relatedness reliably predicts cross-lingual transfer gains in this setting. Across all conditions, pre-adaptation on related auxiliary languages yields no practically meaningful transfer improvements given minimal target-language data, suggesting that linguistic relatedness alone may not reliably predict cross-lingual transfer gains in large multilingual ASR, or constitute an effective strategy for extending such models to low-resource languages.\"/>\n31\t<meta name=\"twitter:site\" content=\"@arxiv\"/>\n32\t<meta name=\"twitter:card\" content=\"summary\"/>\n33\t<meta name=\"twitter:title\" content=\"Evaluating the Effect of Linguistic Relatedness on Cross-Lingual...\"/>\n34\t<meta name=\"twitter:description\" content=\"Extending automatic speech recognition (ASR) to low-resource African languages is constrained by the prohibitive demands of data collection at scale. A promising direction is to leverage...\"/>\n35\t<meta name=\"twitter:image\" content=\"https://static.arxiv.org/icons/twitter/arxiv-logo-twitter-square.png\"/>\n36\t<meta name=\"twitter:image:alt\" content=\"arXiv logo\"/>\n37\t  <link rel=\"stylesheet\" media=\"screen\" type=\"text/css\" href=\"/static/browse/0.3.4/css/tooltip.css\"/><link rel=\"stylesheet\" media=\"screen\" type=\"text/css\" href=\"https://static.arxiv.org/js/bibex-dev/bibex.css?20200709\"/>  <script src=\"/static/browse/0.3.4/js/mathjaxToggle.min.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script>  <script src=\"//code.jquery.com/jquery-latest.min.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script>\n38\t  <script src=\"//cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/js-cookie@2/src/js.cookie.min.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script>\n39\t  <script src=\"//cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/dompurify@2.3.5/dist/purify.min.js\"></script>\n40\t  <script src=\"/static/browse/0.3.4/js/toggle-labs.js?20241022\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script>\n41\t  <script src=\"/static/browse/0.3.4/js/cite.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script><meta name=\"citation_title\" content=\"Evaluating the Effect of Linguistic Relatedness on Cross-Lingual Transfer in Large Multilingual Automatic Speech Recognition\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Florian, Andrei\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Amol, Cynthia Jayne\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Ombaba, Hope Kerubo\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Cui, Xiaoyu\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Mwau, Boniface\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Kamau, Biatus Maina\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Wanzare, Lilian Diana Awuor\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Fellbaum, Christiane\" /><meta name=\"citation_author\" content=\"Buzaaba, Happy\" /><meta name=\"citation_date\" content=\"2026/07/06\" /><meta name=\"citation_online_date\" content=\"2026/07/06\" /><meta name=\"citation_pdf_url\" content=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607.04814\" /><meta name=\"citation_arxiv_id\" content=\"2607.04814\" /><meta name=\"citation_abstract\" content=\"Extending automatic speech recognition (ASR) to low-resource African languages is constrained by the prohibitive demands of data collection at scale. A promising direction is to leverage linguistic relatedness to enhance cross-lingual transfer from a related auxiliary language to the low-resource target by sequentially adapting on both. Although this strategy has shown meaningful improvements in small ASR models, its effectiveness in large ASR remains unclear. We extend this framework to large multilingual ASR through a systematic controlled experimental design spanning six factors, two Africa-centric corpora, and four large ASR models, isolating whether linguistic relatedness reliably predicts cross-lingual transfer gains in this setting. Across all conditions, pre-adaptation on related auxiliary languages yields no practically meaningful transfer improvements given minimal target-language data, suggesting that linguistic relatedness alone may not reliably predict cross-lingual transfer gains in large multilingual ASR, or constitute an effective strategy for extending such models to low-resource languages.\" />\n42\t</head>\n43\t\n44\t<body ><div class=\"flex-wrap-footer\">\n45\t    <a href=\"#content\" class=\"ds-skip-link\">Skip to main content</a>\n46\t  \n47\t  <div class=\"ds-announcement\" id=\"announcement-banner\" role=\"region\"